•
The Plot: Jane Harper is struggling to come out of a depression after her beloved daughter, Mary, died tragically one year ago. But on the eve of her younger (and least favorite) daughter Betsy's high school graduation, Jane is determined to start living her life again. Jane is also determined to find out what happened to Mary - she doesn't believe that Mary fell off a cliff and drowned, she believes that she was pushed. And Jane will stop at nothing to prove it.
•
My Thoughts 💭: Unfortunately, this one missed the mark for me. I found it to be very repetitive and predictable. The book is told through Jane's perspective - she's clearly a psychopath (or sociopath, I can never tell the difference lol). While reading from a psychopath's POV can be fascinating, Jane was SO unlikeable that I had a hard time getting through it (highly recommend reading Jane Doe if you are looking for a psychopath you can root for lol). She did have some sarcastic comments and thoughts that made me laugh, though. I did like the author's writing, so I would be open to trying another one of her books.
